Figures for Patterns of Racial and Educational Assortative Mating in Brazil

Figure 1: Odds ratio of racially exogamous marriage in Brazil and the United States in 2000 among couples where the husband was 2535 years of age. Estimates are based on samples from each countrys 2000 census. A logarithmic scale is used. Error bars are trivially small and are not shown

Figure 2: Bayesian information criterion (BIC) statistic compared with the saturated models for different loglinear models fit to Brazilian marriage data. Lower values indicate superior fit. Black bars indicate the case where browns and blacks are collapsed into a single category. Gray bars indicate the case where browns and blacks are treated separately

Figure 3: Log odds ratios of an interracial marriage in Brazil for unions in which the white spouse is educationally hypergamous or hypogamous relative to a homogamous union. Values are based on log-linear models with and without market exchange parameters in which all brown and black individuals are collapsed into a single nonwhite category. Error bars indicate 95 % confidence intervals

Figure 4: Log-odds ratio of interracial marriage in Brazil for each spouse type when education increases one category. Values are based on log-linear models in which all brown and black individuals have been collapsed into a single nonwhite category. Error bars indicate 95 % confidence intervals

Figure 5: Log odds ratios of an interracial marriage in Brazil for unions in which the lighter spouse is educationally hypergamous or hypogamous relative to a homogamous union. Values are based on log-linear models with and without market exchange parameters. Error bars indicate 95 % confidence intervals

Figure 6: Log-odds ratio of interracial marriage in Brazil for each spouse type when education increases one category. Values are based on log-linear models with separate categories for white, brown, and black. Error bars indicate 95 % confidence intervals
